**Code Explanation:**

The code implements the baseline linear methods (cILC and Wiener Filter) for reconstructing the tSZ Compton-y map from the 6 frequency channels. First, it computes the spectral response vectors for tSZ, kSZ, and the Jy/sr to uK_CMB conversion factors using the provided utils functions. It then identifies the top 5% most massive clusters by finding the maximum tSZ signal in each patch, and splits the remaining patches into training (70%) and validation (15%) sets, reserving the rest plus the top 5% massive clusters for the test set (15%). Using the multiprocessing module with 16 workers, the code efficiently processes the training patches to compute the empirical data covariance matrix (for cILC) and the signal/noise auto- and cross-power spectra (for the Wiener Filter). The mean CIB spectrum is also computed during this pass to serve as the spectral signature to be nulled by the cILC. The cILC weights are calculated by minimizing the variance while enforcing a unit response to the tSZ spectrum and a zero response to the normalized mean CIB spectrum. The Wiener Filter is constructed in harmonic space by computing W(ell) = P_sd(ell) P_dd(ell)^-1 for each multipole bin, which is then interpolated onto a 2D Fourier grid for application to the flat-sky maps. Finally, the baselines are evaluated on the test set. The Mean Squared Error (MSE) and the angular power spectra of the reconstruction residuals are computed and averaged. The results, including the weights and metrics, are saved to disk, and diagnostic plots comparing the reconstructed maps and residual power spectra are generated.

