**Code Explanation:**

The code performs Out-of-Distribution (OOD) stress testing and feature attribution on the trained Super-Resolution Denoising Autoencoder (SR-DAE). 1. High-Noise Identification: It first computes the Root Mean Square (RMS) of the 3000 Simons Observatory (SO) noise realizations across the 90, 150, and 217 GHz channels. It identifies the 95th percentile threshold to isolate the top 5% noisiest realizations. 2. OOD Stress Testing: The model is evaluated on three distinct sets to compute the Mean Squared Error (MSE) of the reconstructed tSZ maps (scaled by 1e6 for numerical stability): Standard Test Set, OOD Massive Clusters, and OOD High Noise. 3. Feature Attribution (Integrated Gradients): An integrated_gradients function is implemented to compute the saliency maps for a high-SNR patch and a low-SNR patch. The gradients of the predicted tSZ sum with respect to the input channels are computed and integrated over 50 interpolation steps from a zero baseline. 4. Null Tests: The model is evaluated on 50 pure noise realizations. The distribution of the predicted pixel values is compared to a zero-mean Gaussian. 5. Visualization: A multi-panel figure is generated and saved, displaying the true tSZ maps alongside the SO and Planck saliency maps, a histogram of the null test output distribution, and a bar chart comparing the MSE across the standard and OOD test sets.

**Modifications:**

Added the required if __name__ == '__main__': block, ensured all paths use the data/ directory, removed LaTeX rendering in matplotlib, and ensured all imports are relative or correctly handled via sys.path.

