**Code Explanation:**

This script transitions the Super-Resolution Denoising Autoencoder (SR-DAE) into a Conditional Diffusion Model (CDM) to learn the probabilistic distribution p(tSZ | Observed, Noise). 1. Architecture: We define a CDM class that wraps the pre-trained SR-DAE backbone. The first convolutional layer is modified to accept 4 channels (3 for SO observations + 1 for the noisy tSZ map x_t). The pre-trained weights from Step 2 are loaded into the corresponding layers, while the new channel is initialized to zero. A time-embedding MLP is added to inject the diffusion timestep t into the bottleneck and decoder layers. 2. Data Normalization: The tSZ maps are scaled by 10^6 and then normalized to zero mean and unit variance using statistics computed from the training set. This ensures the diffusion model operates on a well-behaved target distribution. 3. Training: The CDM is trained using a standard Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Model (DDPM) objective with a linear noise schedule (1000 timesteps). We use mixed-precision training (torch.cuda.amp) to accelerate the process and reduce memory footprint. 4. Generation & Uncertainty Quantification: For the test set, we generate N=10 realizations per patch using Denoising Diffusion Implicit Models (DDIM) sampling with 50 steps, which significantly speeds up inference. We compute the pixel-wise mean and variance maps across these realizations. 5. Mass Proxy: The peak tSZ signal from the ground truth map is extracted for each patch to serve as a proxy for cluster mass, which will be used in Step 5 to evaluate the Y_SZ-M relation. 6. Outputs: The generated CDM means, variance maps, true tSZ maps, peak mass proxies, and deterministic SR-DAE predictions are saved to data/ for the final scientific validation in Step 5.

**Modifications:**

The previous execution failed due to a RuntimeError: unable to allocate shared memory(shm) in the PyTorch DataLoader. This is a common issue when using multiprocessing (num_workers > 0) in environments with limited shared memory. I have modified the DataLoader instantiations for both the training and testing sets to use num_workers=0. This disables multiprocessing for data loading, ensuring that all data is loaded in the main process and avoiding shared memory allocation errors.

